snippet.textDisplay: The only problem with electrics that everyone wants to overlook with the eco-friendly nature of them is where we get our electricity from. We lack the electrical infrastructure to support the power demands of charging an all electric fleet of cars (276.1 million roughly), not to mention that most of our electricity (~81% as of 2018) is produced from fossil fuels. So I have to ask what we actually fix by making our cars electric?

snippet.textDisplay: With gas cars, after watching a race, I can buy a cheap car such as a used Miata or Civic and go to track days myself. With electric cars, after watching a race, there's no electric car I can go to track days with without worrying it breaking down or the cost to fix if it does. I can totally understand electric cars as great daily commuter, but there is too much of a gap between electric car racing and regular electric cars. And EV companies, please stop advertising your cars beating other gas cars when at the same time you void the warranty for track use.

snippet.textDisplay:
What a load of BS.

While VW pulled out of combustion engine based motorsport, Mercedes is adamant they want to extend their presence in F1, McLaren is expanding from F1 into Indycar and possibly even WEC. And the reports about Renault pulling out of F1 were misrepresented in this video, as it had nothing to do with electrification, or what VW announced, but instead is related to the ongoing negotiation of commercial terms with F1's rights owner. Should the new economic terms provided by Liberty Media not be to the satisfaction of Renault, they may pull out of being a constructor, and instead becoming a simple engine supplier.

VW doesn't dictate what the world of motorsports decide.

In any case, we've had cars for 100 years. Doesn't mean people stopped racing horses. F1 will survive into the future as entertainment, as exhibition of skill and bravery, regardless of whether the cars are road relevant anymore.

I'm a big fan of this channel, but there is SO much conspiracy and bs in this video that it really baffles me....Just because VW is the biggest shareholder in the other brands (Porsche, Lambo, Audi...and therefore "owns" them) doesn't mean that those will pull their worksteams out of combustion motorsports, too!
Those are still their own companies and can deal with their motorsport divisions INDEPENDANTLY!!
Audi is still Audi, Porsche is still Porsche, a Panigale is still not running a 1.8 TDI...

And I'm pretty sure Mercedes won't stop on ALL their engine developments...that's just for road cars...But since there is not a single electric commercial 40-ton truck on the streets atm, i HIGHLY doubt they'll stop development on their commercial truck engines any time soon


This video is nothing but hype, speculation, and rumors...thumbs down
